Text:
 @fenneckw  
If you mainly play your kernel level anti cheat gooner games than yeah Linux won't work for you.
Majority of games on Steam run perfectly fine though.

Should have just called the 5070ti a 5070 and the 5070 a 5060.
Like why the fuck didn't they do that? :{
(Ok, I know.. bullshit marketing like always, but still...)

@aquathecolor  
I only play offline 
I play games to get away from people 😆

 @zealgaming8161  Pricing from years ago doesn't equate to a product "aging well." The entire 30 series sold out throughout the pandemic years and was being scalped due to Covid and more demand than supply. 

In reality, the 3090 didn't age well at all. The 3080 TI rendered it pointless to buy one unless you needed the extra 8 GB of VRAM and 1-5% more performance, and the 4090 absolutely stomped the 3090 in performance. 

It's hilarious how many people are still trying to sell their 3090s on Facebook for $800+.

 @rarespetrusamartean5433  My rx580 cost 230 bucks, 8gigs of gdrr5. About 8 years ago. 16gb is the absolute minimum you should spend money on. End of story. Not debatable. 
32gb should be mainstream and 64gb should be available on the high end, but the graphics card market is completely out to lunch.
Smartphone memory has incresed 4-6 times, for the same priced models, in the same time frame.

 @Doncolto  even if I was in the market for a new gpu I wouldn't buy nvidia, mostly because of how much contempt for the consumer they have, but also because out of the three options, AMD have the best support for Linux out of the box.

Alas, I already have a 7800XT so I'm happy for a few years yet.

I'm really only watching reviews to point and laugh at the train wreck that is the 5000 series launch and support the content creators who've put a tonne of effort into the content they've put out.

@jasonhurdlow6607   Oh really, that's interesting.

Historically the "New 70" would rival the "Old 80Ti" even going back to the 2011 / 28nm cards. It seems like the 50 series is Nvidia's lowest point for consumers. I would rank it as such: RTX-50, RTX-20, RTX-40, GTX-7, RTX-30, GTX-10, GTX-6, GTX-9.

Thank goodness for channels like Hardware Unboxed for doing the work, and spreading the truth.

@duarteribeiro1520  No. The 4070 vs 5070
The 4070 super against 5070 super. When it comes out.
Hes just trying to make it look worse than it is. Hates NVIDIA

 @Fudgesickle  I'm missing the part where i praise amd in any way or form.

The fact that nvidia is bad doesn't make amd better, they are just manipulating the price, i would add tsmc too to the variables.

It's the entire market that need to change, but people still buy every card at every price, doesn't matter what.

 @kevinerbs2778  Mostly because it is added value. DLSS is way better than FSR 3.1 (we dont know about 4), more widely available. Nvidias drivers, at least in the past have proven to have less issues overall. Cuda is important to those who need it etc.  RT performance is also better. 

AMD also has its own value proposition: Linux drivers - if you are building a linux PC, you're better off buying amd.

In the end you are making the decision for yourself, but to say that nvidia does not have more advantages than amd when it comes to their cards would be dishonest.

 @awadepanela4401  Que lo prueben en juegos sin esa tecnología.
Tenerla, y usar solo el rasterizado si más, me parece una boludez.
Y estos techtubes solo arman polémca por que viven de eso.

 @axis2065  I actually switched from a 4060 to a 5060 Ti, and yeah, I played BF6 on the 4060 — visuals and FPS were way better than on consoles. I think your issue is with the CPU or RAM, not the VRAM.

Don’t get me wrong — yeah, 8GB might look a bit low these days, especially since some games are already close to using 7GB. But for now and probably for the next year or two, it’s not really a problem. I’ll just upgrade later when it becomes one.

Everyone’s hating on 8GB, but honestly, I think that’s kind of nonsense. I had the same dilemma back in the day with the 1060 — 3GB vs 6GB — and I went with the 3GB version. It lasted me for years without any real issues.

 @Person-jo9ey  So we have to use upscaling because there isn't enough VRAM on the card? 
It's also about future proofing. 
There is no  reason NOT to put at least 16GB of VRAM on any card other than gouging. What do you think is the cost of 12GB vs 16GB of VRAM for nvidia and AMD (who sadly chose to fall in step rather than rise above the VRAM skimping)?

 @zWORMzGaming  love you bro
i watch you
since 2020

 @UM_88-s2c  Since you can't read, let me repeat it for you: 7950X3D (and by extent the 9950X3D) is MUCH more expensive. the 7900X3D is a lot more cost effective.
9950X3D costs 800€, while i paid 380€ for my 7900X3D. I don't desperately need the best CPU available so saving A TON for a small loss in performance.

Let me guess you're the type of person who would buy a 5090 for scalpeled prices above double the MSRP because "you dont have any choice" and "money doesnt matter". If you want to waste money, feel free to do so, but the argument "just get" is literally the dumbest words anyone can take in their mouth.

 @DailyCorvid  I do have a 4070, which i bought in 2022 and i hate using upscaling, because it defeats the whole purpose of 4K. I care mostly about sharp geometric edges and better UI scaling, like in Space Engineers, where i'm building large structures out of cuboid objects. Or base building in No Man's Sky, lots of edges and shapes. All the updates made the game more heavy to run. The 4070 struggles with base rendering and texture loading even with upscaling nonsense turned on. 

I began playing in 4K with a 770ti 4GB, which was a 350€ card. 4GB was plenty in this era. No upscaling and with medium-high-custom settings every game i played ran fine.

//edited: typo

@pkpnyt4711  if the wafer is that large compared to the 7600 or 4060 then shouldn't it have more power then those cards by quite a bit?

To be fair though Intel hasn't been in the GPU market very long either. So it makes sense for them to have inefficiencies.

Hopefully with celestial they would have refined their production to create smaller wafers and have a more powerful, smaller package

 @Tom_Quixote $500 is budget price for Nvidia!
Now I did fix it for you!
😂

 @karthik7282  I got the best I could for 1080p gaming, and it just happens to have that refresh rate capability. Can I tell the difference between my older 144 hz monitor? For everyday stuff apart from gaming heck yes. Everything seems a lot smother and just better. 
As far as gaming....well. It's a high quality monitor so the colors, black and light levels etc are absolutely fantastic but I guess how it feels would depend on the game. How a game "feels" is dependent on FPS yeah? Some games are locked at a certain FPS so anything above 144hz is kinda like overkill. I guess. I'm no expert. 
For me it was well worth the money and I'm very happy with it.

@cxngo8124  yes and they are very expensive 
$900 for 5070 
And $1000 for 9070xt and no non xt

 @tomthomas3499  I'm planning on getting a 5070; 12GB is enough for the games I play.
The super version, without a significant chip upgrade, is pointless and will definitely be more expensive.
By the time the super versions become cheaper, the 6000 series will be released, and everything will start all over again.

 @coasty2k  defo stick with 1440p. I tried it on a 4k TV. It can pull good FPS on older games, but for newer ones you definitely need DLSS for smooth 60 and framegen. 
And I definitely felt motion sickness when running on DLSS and framegen for games that have swords with First Person Camera, guns, not so much. Not much motion sickness when playing car games however. Do note i'm running max settings with ray tracing.
I advise you here since if you're going 4k gaming, you also need 4k textures in older games and they are double in install size and adds storage cost. You also need GOOD 4k monitors which to me imo, is still overpriced. 4k is still expensive except for videos. Even VR is cheaper at the moment.

 @ProcyonAlpha  I kid you not, I sold my 4070 for $800 CAD, and then immedietly bought a brand new 5070 for $750 Cad. (i bought the 4070 for $600 a few months back originally)
Meanwhile 9070's are litterally $900 to $1k.

The GPU market is genuinely insane. Makes zero sense, but hey got an upgrade outta it.

 @bonitaritz7052  I've had my new PC for a few days so far, I've tried Star Wars Outlaws, it runs nicely even on a 4K monitor, but it's not without compromise. I used the recommended settings by Nvidia app which optimizes the game and the game looks good and FPS is mostly above 100. 
It really depends a lot on how one plays with the settings, but otherwise for the price I'd say it's a good graphics card. 
I'm satisfied.

@LeaveMyGun  brother I dunno what to tell u 

Just search 4070 super vs 3090 

They're the same card albeit 3090 has 24 gb ram

 @VDA19  If you play the waiting game; you'll always be waiting.  How much longer can a person on a GTX card wait; these games are requiring RT now.  5070 supers are 2 years out, and when they do come; good luck getting one at MSRP.  I just got a 5070 at $600.  It's plenty worth it.

Obviously the card you currently have is the determining factor here.

The 1070 is struggling to get 60 fps at low settings at 1080p on todays games. Marvel Rivals look like dog poo and has frame times up to 35ms during certain situations at 1080p with sub 1080p render scale. The 5070 lets you max most of them with DLSS and no frame gen at 4k and get 60 fps with normal 11ms frame times.  Huge improvement.  Telling anybody in that situation to wait is just stupid.  I don't need to future proof; 600$ is a perfectly good price to replace it in 2-3 years if I wanted to, with something that's better, and then I could actually wait for the prices to stabilize.  I'd love a 5090 TI SUPER DUPER, but it's not worth 3,500$.  I could buy a honda and do a motor swap with a turbo for that money.... like, what?

 @beaniesigmar3908  the 5070 is like 600€ in France, this is not an overpriced GPU for what it's capable of at its designed resolution : 1440P, with DLSS, framegen and RT you could get away with 140-160fps in most games (framegen X2).

People think AMD's card is something special because they had generational uplift, but they only had an uplift for RT performance, their VRAM is still ddr6, they still only have 16GB of VRAM and their rt performance is still lacking. Can't blame NVIDIA for barely having a progression when the node size is the same and they already had an amazing product.

Meanwhile amd had a shitty upscaler, shitty RT performance, so yeah, it's not hard to upgrade from shit to decent, it's harder to upgrade from great to amazing. And this is why Nvidia gets hated by people who can't afford a computer in a world where everything gets more expensive.

 @NanayaTorch   Sure. Makes sense. Similar die size to the 3060. Same 192-Bit memory bus and 12GB of VRAM. Probably should be called the 5060 by that logic and cost $330-350.
Except in that fantasy world, the much loved RX 9060 XT should be called the 9050 and cost $220-240. And the 9070 (which is only 10% faster than this and costs more in my region) should be the 9060 XT.
It's all well and good preaching product A should be called X and not Y, but saying a 5070 should be a 5060 and not complaining about the AMD stuff is absolutely stupid
